<h3>Status&nbsp;</h3>
<p><span style="font-size:11.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Segoe UI Historic&quot;">India’s poor share in global trade (<span style="color:#e84c22">2.1</span>%), especially on goods, is a reflection of our acute lack of competitiveness.</span></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size:11.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Segoe UI Historic&quot;"><span style="color:#e84c22">Reasons for poor exports</span> - weak global demand&nbsp; (13%) + Domestic bottleneck&nbsp; (50%)+ Overvalued rupee (17%)</span></span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-size:11.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Segoe UI Historic&quot;"><span style="color:#e84c22">IMPROVE COMPETITIVENESS -</span></span></span></p>
<ol>
<li><span style="font-size:11.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Segoe UI Historic&quot;"><em><strong>LABOUR INTENSIVE EXPORT </strong></em>= revive textile exports can be helped by increasing <em><strong>productivity</strong></em> in cotton plantations (by better implementing available technology, for example BT Cotton</span></span></li>
<li><em><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Segoe UI Historic&quot;">&nbsp;</span></span></strong></em><span style="font-size:11.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Segoe UI Historic&quot;"><em><strong>Trade negotiations</strong></em> (bilateral, multilateral and plurilateral) to lower tariffs</span></span><br />
<span style="font-size:11.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Segoe UI Historic&quot;">&nbsp;</span></span><span style="font-size:11.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Segoe UI Historic&quot;">India has gained from trade agreements: a 0.7 per cent increase per year in trade surplus with partner countries for manufactured products and 2.3 per cent per year for total merchandise”.</span></span></li>
<li><span style="font-size:11.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Segoe UI Historic&quot;">&nbsp;</span></span><span style="font-size:11.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Segoe UI Historic&quot;">Survey singled out China as a model for India to emulate. “China’s remarkable export performance vis-à-vis India is driven primarily by <em><strong>deliberate specialization </strong></em>at large scale in labour-intensive activities, especially ‘network products’, where production occurs across Global Value Chains (GVCs) operated by multi-national corporations”.</span></span></li></ol>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h3>Measures taken so far = PLI (policy, logistics, infrastructure) - as per ES2021</h3>
<p>Basic to increase export = exports competitiveness.&nbsp;</p>
<ol>
<li>POLICY / schemes
<ol>
<li>TFA + FTP 2015-2020</li>
<li>[[RoDTEP]] +&nbsp; &nbsp;Single Window Facilitation</li>
<li>domestic manuf + export = PLI&nbsp;<span style="color:#e67e22">focussed intervention in export promotion via PLI&nbsp;</span></li>
<li>Assemble in India and GVC part.</li>
<li>12 Champion sector in services.</li></ol></li>
<li>LOGISTICS
<ol>
<li>LPI of WB (44 rank) + <u><em>trading across border </em></u>in EoDB of WB - one of highest improvement</li>
<li>Faceless assessment 'turant customs' + RFID, FASTag + e-SANCHIT + niryat Bandhu&nbsp;</li>
<li>Digital = iLOG (Indian Logistics Platform) = INTEGRATE , Freight operations of Indian railway + VAHAN of MoRTH + Port COmmunity System + DFCs</li>
<li>Role of <span style="color:#f1c40f">private</span> investment in supply chain</li></ol></li>
<li>INFRA&nbsp;
<ol>
<li>Bharatmala + Sagarmala + Multi modal logistic park (Jogighopa , Assam) + DFCs + TIES (trade infra for export scheme)</li></ol></li>
<li>Assemble in India to move up value chain of exports as proposed by Budget 2019-20</li></ol>
